              <h2>How this loans &amp; debt payoff planner works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool lets you enter multiple debts (credit cards, personal
                loans, auto loans, student loans, etc.) and simulate:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>How long it will take to become debt-free.</li>
                <li>How much interest you will pay in total.</li>
                <li>How different payoff strategies change the result.</li>
                <li>Whether a consolidation loan could save you money.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Payoff strategies supported</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Debt avalanche:</strong> Extra money goes to the
                  highest APR first. This usually minimizes total interest.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Debt snowball:</strong> Extra money goes to the
                  smallest balance first. This can provide faster psychological
                  wins.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Proportional to balance:</strong> Extra money is split
                  across debts in proportion to their balances.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Formulas used</h3>
              <p>For each debt, interest is calculated monthly using:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Monthly interest rate</strong>:</p>
                <p>r = APR / 12 / 100</p>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>Interest for the month</strong>:</p>
                <p>interest = balance × r</p>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>Principal paid</strong>:</p>
                <p>principal = payment − interest</p>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>New balance</strong>:</p>
                <p>new balance = balance − principal</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The simulation runs month by month, always covering minimum
                payments first. Any extra payment is allocated according to your
                chosen strategy until all balances reach zero.
              </p>

              <h3>Consolidation loan calculation</h3>
              <p>
                For the consolidation scenario, we assume you borrow exactly the
                sum of your current balances (ignoring closing timing
                differences) plus any upfront fees you enter.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Loan amount</strong>:</p>
                <p>L = sum of current balances</p>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>Monthly rate</strong>:</p>
                <p>r = APR / 12 / 100</p>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>Number of payments</strong>:</p>
                <p>n = years × 12</p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>Monthly payment</strong> (amortizing loan):
                </p>
                <p>Payment = L × r / (1 − (1 + r)<sup>−n</sup>)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Total interest is the sum of all payments minus the principal,
                plus any upfront fees you entered.
              </p>

              <h2>When consolidation can make sense</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  You qualify for a <strong>lower APR</strong> than your current
                  weighted-average rate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  You keep the <strong>same or shorter term</strong>, so you are
                  not just stretching payments over more years.
                </li>
                <li>
                  You are confident you will
                  <strong>not run up new balances</strong> on the old credit
                  cards.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                If the new APR is similar or higher, or if fees are large,
                consolidation may cost more overall even if the monthly payment
                is lower.
              </p>

