              <h2>FAQ: Managing loans and debt</h2>

              <h3>Should I consolidate my debt?</h3>
              <p>
                Consolidation can be helpful if it lowers your interest rate,
                simplifies multiple payments into one, and you can commit to not
                adding new debt. Use the planner above to compare your current
                path with a consolidation loan including fees.
              </p>

              <h3>Is avalanche or snowball better?</h3>
              <p>
                Avalanche usually saves more interest because it targets the
                highest APR first. Snowball can be better for motivation if you
                need quick wins from closing out small balances. The best
                strategy is the one you can stick with consistently.
              </p>

              <h3>What is a good debt-to-income (DTI) ratio?</h3>
              <p>
                Many lenders like to see total DTI below about 36%, with 43%
                often considered a common upper limit for mortgage underwriting.
                However, acceptable thresholds vary by lender, loan type, and
                your overall profile.
              </p>

              <h3>How often should I revisit my payoff plan?</h3>
              <p>
                Revisit your plan whenever your income, expenses, or interest
                rates change, or at least every few months. Increasing your
                extra payment, even slightly, can shave months or years off your
                payoff timeline.
              </p>
